Pursuant to C.R.S. §6-1-1706, the Office of the Attorney General is investigating potential violations of the Colorado Artificial Intelligence Act in consumer lending. Within thirty (30) days, please produce:

(1) A complete inventory of every Covered Automated Decisionmaking Tool used in the underwriting, pricing, or adverse-action determination for Colorado consumer credit applications between April 1, 2025 and April 1, 2026;

(2) The §1702 developer documentation packets for each Tool, including any redactions and the basis therefor;

(3) Aggregate adverse-outcome statistics by protected class for the period above;

(4) Records of all consumer reconsideration requests received under §1705 and their disposition; and

(5) The §1704(3) post-adverse-outcome disclosures sent to Colorado consumers, or evidence of ECOA/Reg B equivalence relied upon in lieu thereof.

Responses may be produced via secure portal. This office's cure-period analysis under §1706(3) will commence upon receipt.

Pursuant to NYC Administrative Code §20-870 et seq. and the rules promulgated thereunder, the Department of Consumer and Worker Protection is conducting a compliance audit of your use of Automated Employment Decision Tools (AEDTs) for candidates seeking employment in the City of New York. Within thirty (30) days, please produce:

(1) A complete inventory of every AEDT used in candidate sourcing, screening, ranking, or selection for New York City positions between May 1, 2025 and May 1, 2026;

(2) The most recent independent bias audit for each AEDT, including the auditor's independence attestation;

(3) Evidence of the pre-use candidate notice required under §20-871(b), including the data type, source, and retention policy notice elements;

(4) Records of all candidate requests for accommodation or alternative selection processes; and

(5) Any vendor-supplied compliance packets relied upon, with redactions noted.

Non-compliance is subject to civil penalties of up to $1,500 per violation per day.

Pursuant to Cal. Civ. Code §1798.155 and the ADMT regulations promulgated by this Agency, the California Privacy Protection Agency is investigating Pinetop Motors USA's use of automated decisionmaking technology in the vehicle customer lifecycle. Within thirty (30) days, please produce:

(1) A complete inventory of every ADMT used in California consumer decisions over the prior twelve months — including but not limited to pre-qualification, captive financing (Pinetop MAC), trade-in valuation, predictive service offers, connected-vehicle behavioral segmentation, and any in-cabin driver-monitoring tools;

(2) The pre-use notices presented to California consumers under the ADMT regs §7220, including any embedded in the connected-vehicle activation flow;

(3) For every captive-finance adverse-action determination, the §1704-equivalent statement of personal-information categories used — and a statement of whether any vehicle-telematics data was treated as a financing signal;

(4) Records of consumer access and correction requests under CCPA §1798.110, including any requests directed at the ADMT-specific access right;

(5) The independent or self-administered risk assessment(s) for each high-risk ADMT under the CPPA risk-assessment regulation;

(6) For any in-cabin biometric data collected by driver-monitoring systems, the CCPA biometric-information disclosure and the basis for retention.

This Agency is coordinating with the Colorado Attorney General's Office on parallel ADMT inquiries; responsive material may be cross-produced. Non-compliance may result in administrative fines up to $7,500 per intentional violation.
